<article>
    <h1>BIG FISH BACKUP</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-09"><time>2020-11-09</time></a>
        - <span>HOME IN FOCUS</span>
        - <span role="byline">Alphon&#xAD;sus Ch&#xAD;ern Ex&#xAD;ec&#xAD;u&#xAD;tive Pho&#xAD;to&#xAD;jour&#xAD;nal&#xAD;ist achern@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Bar­ra­mundi Asia, which runs one of the big­gest fish farms in the world, has do­nated fish worth $9,000 to a lo­cal farm as part of a pro­gramme to help op­er­a­tors stay afloat dur­ing the Covid-19 cri­sis. The Straits Times fol­lows the fish on their jour­ney from the nurs­ery to a float­ing farm.</p>
    <p>TUR­BU­LENT WA­TERS</p>
    <p>It has been a dif­fi­cult time for fish farm­ers in Sin­ga­pore since the lo­cal food and bev­er­age in­dus­try slowed down due to Covid-19. These bar­ra­mundi fin­ger­lings will help us to con­serve our cash flow, and we are hop­ing to pro­duce up to 19 tonnes of fish this year.</p>
    <p>EN­TREPRENEUR SEAN CHIA, who owns float­ing fish farm EG Fish­ery, on the do­na­tion from Bar­ra­mundi Asia.</p>
    <p>To sup­port the lo­cal aqua­cul­ture in­dus­try, home-grown com­pany Bar­ra­mundi Asia do­nated more than half a tonne of fin­ger­lings to a fish farm last month.</p>
    <p>It marked the first of sev­eral such ex­er­cises that the com­pany plans to carry out over the com­ing year.</p>
    <p>The in­au­gu­ral ex­er­cise saw the Sin­ga­pore fish breeder, which started in 2008 and is now one of the largest bar­ra­mundi farms in the world, give away 2,000 ju­ve­nile fish worth about $9,000 to EG Fish­ery, a float­ing farm owned by en­trepreneur Sean Chia.</p>
    <p>Fin­ger­lings are about 10cm in length, with fully de­vel­oped fins and scales.</p>
    <p>“It has been a dif­fi­cult time for fish farm­ers in Sin­ga­pore since the lo­cal food and bev­er­age in­dus­try slowed down due to Covid-19,” said Mr Chia.</p>
    <p>“These bar­ra­mundi fin­ger­lings will help us to con­serve our cash flow, and we are hop­ing to pro­duce up to 19 tonnes of fish this year,” he added.</p>
    <p>The fin­ger­lings were bred by start-up com­pany Al­le­gro Aqua’s land-based nurs­ery at the Sin­ga­pore Food Agency’s Ma­rine Aqua­cul­ture Cen­tre on St John’s Is­land.</p>
    <p>They are a spe­cially de­vel­oped strain and sur­vive bet­ter with­out an­tibi­otics, said Mr Andy Tan, as­sis­tant hatch­ery man­ager at Al­le­gro Aqua.</p>
    <p>This helps farm­ers to lower their pro­duc­tion costs, he added.</p>
    <p>Al­le­gro Aqua is a fully owned sub­sidiary of Bar­ra­mundi Asia, which ac­quired the com­pany in March.</p>
    <p>The com­ing dona­tions to other farms will in­clude fish weigh­ing 30g to 200g each, in quan­ti­ties worth up to $30,000, said Mr An­dreas von Scholten, chief ex­ec­u­tive of Bar­ra­mundi Asia.</p>
    <p>“We want to play our part in grow­ing Sin­ga­pore’s aqua­cul­ture ecosys­tem.</p>
    <p>“On top of sup­port­ing l ocal farm­ers through this dif­fi­cult pe­riod, these dona­tions are also part of our ef­forts in con­tribut­ing to­wards Sin­ga­pore’s long-term food se­cu­rity.”</p>
    <p>CAST­ING SAFETY NETS We want to play our part in grow­ing Sin­ga­pore’s aqua­cul­ture ecosys­tem. On top of sup­port­ing lo­cal farm­ers through this dif­fi­cult pe­riod, these dona­tions are also part of our ef­forts in con­tribut­ing to­wards Sin­ga­pore’s long-term food se­cu­rity.</p>
    <p>MR AN­DREAS VON SCHOLTEN, chief ex­ec­u­tive of Bar­ra­mundi Asia, on lend­ing a help­ing hand.</p>

